# Flight Path — repository-level environment example
#
# The application database (Postgres 16) is hosted REMOTELY on the trashcan
# Mac Pro and reached over Tailscale. It is NOT started locally.
#
# Connection details (the application reads these from web/.env and
# node-worker/.env, NOT from this file):
#
#   Host:   100.117.75.7           (trashcan Mac Pro, Tailscale IP)
#   Port:   5432
#   DB:     flightpath
#   User:   flightpath_user
#   TLS:    none at the PG layer — Tailscale already encrypts the wire
#           (DATABASE_URL uses ?sslmode=disable for that reason)
#
# Example DATABASE_URL (real password lives only in web/.env and
# node-worker/.env, never committed):
#
#   DATABASE_URL=postgres://flightpath_user:PASSWORD@100.117.75.7:5432/flightpath?sslmode=disable
#
# To rotate or look up the password: it is stored in 1Password as
# "Flight Path DB user (trashcan)". To reset it, SSH into the trashcan
# and run, as the `ops` superuser:
#
#   ssh trashcan
#   sudo docker exec -it trashcan_postgres psql -U ops -d postgres -c \
#     "ALTER ROLE flightpath_user WITH LOGIN PASSWORD '<new_pw>';"
#
# Then update DATABASE_URL in web/.env and node-worker/.env on every
# dev machine and restart the app.
#
# (This file previously held POSTGRES_USER / POSTGRES_PASSWORD / etc. for a
# local Docker container. That container was retired — see README.md.)
